The paper discusses phishing attacks and anti-phishing tools, which are related to computer security (cs.CR). The focus of the paper is on educating users to detect and avoid phishing attacks, which involves human-computer interaction (cs.HC). The paper also discusses the use of a gaming prototype to enhance users' self-efficacy, which is related to cyberpsychology (cs.CY). The paper uses social cognitive theory to explore the relationship between knowledge attributes and self-efficacy, which is related to social and information sciences (cs.SI). Finally, the paper proposes a theoretical framework and a gamified approach, which are related to game theory (cs.GT).
